Her verse reframes everything: she wasnâ€™t cold â€” she was hurt, dismissed, and now done. And when she walks away and her paint fades completely, it shows sheâ€™s free, while he remains stuck in guilt and realization â€” still painted, still invisible. I say this rarely, in fact never. But this song is in fact perfect. Being almost entirely composed from other songs it is a sampled collage of fleeting and incomplete memories that are warped and layered over one another, creating a tightly woven tapestry of the past. It is all the best bits of memories roughly yet passionately stitched together to create a masterpiece that is not just a break up song, but THE break up song. Every millisecond of this song evokes every memory of everyone I have loved and lost in my journey to understand who I am and what I am to share with the world. Many songs have lyrical mastery, harmonic adeptness or just pure soul, but this song has everything all firmly baked into it's very being. This is timeless art and was instantly recognized by everyone as such, even if they didn't outwardly realize it immediately. Pure genius.

The remix gained popularity, debuting on Billboard charts and becoming a crowd favorite at events like Coachella.  ï¿¼ ï¿¼ Additionally, Gotye has been involved in preserving electronic music history through his Brooklyn-based nonprofit, Forgotten Futures. I've read about the debate of whether there's a love triangle in this song, but I believe Gotye and Kimbra are actually singing directly to each other about their shared relationship. When Kimbra sings "You said that you could let it go and I wouldn't catch you hung up on somebody that you used to know," she's cleverly throwing Gotye's own words back at him. She's saying "You claimed you'd move on easily and I wouldn't find you still obsessing over me (someone you used to know)." Her verse isn't introducing a third person - it's giving us her perspective on the same breakup, suggesting he manipulated her and made her feel everything was her fault. This interpretation makes the song so much more powerful as a two-sided breakup story where each person feels wronged in different ways.

Relationships (even marriages) seem to end one of two ways. Both individuals realize the relationship is no longer working, and agree to go their separate ways...sometimes even remaining as friends. The alternative is fraught with anger/resentment/distrust/extreme bitterness...sometimes even hate. The emotional toll is huge, as the relationship tears itself apart and disrupts every aspect of life. Eventually the smoke clears, and things resume some sense of normalcy...for many. But there are those who never recover...despite the ugly words and emotional outbursts, they remain deeply in love with their now departed 'adversary'. Seventeen years have passed since my divorce...and I still love her. My life is good, and I have few complaints...but  there remains a huge empty space that will never be filled.

This is one of the most beautiful music videos ever. I once saw someone explaining this music video. This is about a couple arguing and pinning blames onto each other. Though quite evident from the song itself, the music video takes the narration to another level. The slow painting of the walls with both the man and woman indicate the "building of a relationship". But when she moves towards him, it indicates a small breakage in the relationship. The woman singing "Ahhh" in the background while the man continuing to sing his proper lyrics indicates his refusal to listen to her explanation, sort of an ego clash. Towards the end, she gives up and goes back to her position and starts getting rid of the paint, which shows that she no longer is a part of the "relationship they had built together". Also, the man refuses to look at the woman until the end in the music video, which indicates his realisation of losing the woman he loves. So beautiful.
